node.text:
Watch to learn how @beholdingeye captured his favorite photo on the Canon Road Trip.
 
"The lighting was optimal for shooting waterfalls in the gorge this day; mostly cloudy with filtered light. With these conditions, I used my 4 stop neutral density filter paired with a polarizing filter. Filters allow the photographer to achieve the desired effect they are envisioning. By using a neutral density filter I could increase my shutter speed to smooth out the water, and cut through the glare on top of the water at the same time.
 
Do you use filters to work around difficult light?“

node.title: Canon Road Trip: Photo Review with Paul Seibert

node.text: Find out what’s in #CanonExplorerOfLight @vanessajoy’s gear bag, or in this case gear closet! "After 20 years of accumulating photography gear, I was getting sick and tired of rearranging bags (and finding lost gear) for each type of shoot. I finally found the perfect solution in having a gear cabinet, instead of a gear bag. Now I can grab exactly what tools I need for the type of photoshoot I'm going on, without playing the 'which bag is my 50mm 1.2 in?' game. Best thing I've ever done!"

node.text:
Photo by #CanonExplorerOfLight @larettahouston: "There is beauty in everyone and playing with light patterns gives a picture a more unique look that will catch anyone’s eye. Some of my best photos are the ones that are done in a studio with nothing planned but to photograph strong work. 

This is one of the rare times I decided at the last minute to photograph beauty and work with light and pattern. Here I placed a Gobo on a strobe at a 45-degree angle but close to the model and feathered a 40” Octabox to light the model and the background. I also wanted to make sure that I adjusted the pattern to have the biggest star to her eye just right. I am very happy with this image as I can see that it would work as part of a beauty campaign, magazine editorial, or even a possible artist CD cover."

📸 #Canon EOS 5DS
Lens: EF 24-70mm f/2.8L II USM

node.text:
Photo by @thereal_rem: "I love images of lighthouses, there is something about them that is very enticing. I took a trip with my parents from Alabama to Maine to see the northeast coast. As I was out shooting photos of Nubble Lighthouse, a man walking his dog came by. It was easily one of the cutest dogs I've seen. The dog came over and sniffed my camera and when I talked to him, he jumped up on me and let me pet him. I asked the man if I could get some shots of his dog in front of this beautiful landscape. He was more than happy to agree!" #ShotOnCanon

📸 #Canon EOS R
Lens: RF50mm F1.8 STM
